**Converted cursor-based implementation:**

```javascript
// Helper: encode compound cursor as URL-safe base64 JSON
function encodeCursor(createdAt, id) {
    // Normalize createdAt to ISO string (handles Date objects from DB drivers)
    const created_at = createdAt instanceof Date 
        ? createdAt.toISOString() 
        : createdAt;

    const cursorObj = { created_at, id };
    const json = JSON.stringify(cursorObj);

    // URL-safe base64 (avoids +, /, = issues in query params)
    return Buffer.from(json)
        .toString('base64')
        .replace(/\+/g, '-')
        .replace(/\//g, '_')
        .replace(/=/g, '');
}

// Helper: decode and validate cursor
function decodeCursor(cursorStr) {
    if (typeof cursorStr !== 'string' || cursorStr.length === 0) {
        throw new Error('Cursor must be a non-empty string');
    }

    try {
        // Restore standard base64
        let b64 = cursorStr.replace(/-/g, '+').replace(/_/g, '/');
        while (b64.length % 4 !== 0) {
            b64 += '=';
        }

        const json = Buffer.from(b64, 'base64').toString('utf8');
        const parsed = JSON.parse(json);

        if (
            !parsed ||
            typeof parsed.created_at === 'undefined' ||
            typeof parsed.id === 'undefined'
        ) {
            throw new Error('Invalid cursor structure');
        }

        // Basic type validation for the compound key
        if (typeof parsed.created_at !== 'string') {
            throw new Error('Invalid cursor: created_at must be a string');
        }
        if (typeof parsed.id !== 'number' && typeof parsed.id !== 'string') {
            throw new Error('Invalid cursor: id must be number or string');
        }

        return { created_at: parsed.created_at, id: parsed.id };
    } catch (err) {
        throw new Error('Malformed cursor');
    }
}

// GET /api/posts?limit=20&after=<cursor>
async function getPosts(req, res) {
    // Parse limit (no page param)
    const rawLimit = parseInt(req.query.limit, 10);
    const limit = isNaN(rawLimit) || rawLimit < 1 ? 20 : Math.min(rawLimit, 100);
    const after = req.query.after;

    let cursor = null;
    if (after) {
        try {
            cursor = decodeCursor(after);
        } catch (err) {
            return res.status(400).json({ error: 'Invalid or malformed cursor' });
        }
    }

    const queryLimit = limit + 1; // N+1 trick

    // Build query with keyset pagination (no OFFSET anywhere)
    let sql = `
        SELECT id, title, content, author_id, created_at 
        FROM posts 
        WHERE published = true
    `;
    const params = [];

    if (cursor) {
        sql += ` AND (created_at, id) < ($1, $2)`;
        params.push(cursor.created_at, cursor.id);
    }

    // LIMIT placeholder is always the next available $N
    sql += ` ORDER BY created_at DESC, id DESC LIMIT $${params.length + 1}`;
    params.push(queryLimit);

    const result = await db.query(sql, params);
    let posts = result.rows;

    // Apply N+1 logic
    const hasMore = posts.length > limit;
    if (hasMore) {
        posts = posts.slice(0, limit);
    }

    // Build pagination response
    const pagination = {
        hasMore,
        limit
    };

    if (hasMore && posts.length > 0) {
        const last = posts[posts.length - 1];
        pagination.nextCursor = encodeCursor(last.created_at, last.id);
    }

    res.json({
        posts,
        pagination
    });
}
```

**Why cursor-based pagination is superior here:**

- **Performance**: `OFFSET` forces the database to scan and discard `page * limit` rows every time (O(n) cost that grows with depth). The cursor version uses a `WHERE (created_at, id) < (...)` predicate that can be satisfied with an index seek on the `(created_at, id)` composite index — constant-time "jump" to the right spot regardless of how deep you paginate.
- **Consistency under concurrency**: With offset pagination, inserts/deletes at the top of the result set cause the client to see skipped rows or duplicates when they request the "next" page. Cursor pagination uses the actual column values as a stable bookmark, so the view of "what comes after this exact row" remains correct even as the table mutates.
- **No expensive COUNT**: The original `COUNT(*)` is a full table (or index) scan and becomes very costly on large tables. Cursor pagination naturally signals "end of data" via the N+1 fetch without ever computing a total.
- **Better UX for modern clients**: Ideal for infinite scroll, "load more", and real-time feeds. Clients just carry the opaque `nextCursor` string; they don't have to manage page numbers that can become invalid.

The implementation strictly follows all stated requirements (compound `(created_at, id)` cursor, base64, N+1, no `OFFSET`, no `COUNT`, graceful 400 on bad cursors, correct response shape, etc.).
